{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532485","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532485"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:26:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:26:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14684"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14684","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14684"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.63,0.04,0.14,0.04,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7377"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112762"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7377"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14684"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94796"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1150"},{"type":"tags","id":"1306"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"3053"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18004"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37366"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41948"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46356"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112762"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with his partner reporting that he has been hearing voices for the past three days. He has been drinking heavily for 15 years, consuming approximately one bottle of spirits daily. He reports hearing multiple male voices making threatening comments and discussing his actions prominent when he is drinking. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears anxious but oriented. His pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 138/88 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He is not tremulous and there are no focal neurological signs. He has good insight into his current situation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Substance-induced psychotic disorder","Early-onset schizophrenia","Alcohol withdrawal delirium","Drug-induced delirium","Acute paranoid psychosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with auditory hallucinations in the context of chronic alcohol use. The key features supporting \u003Cstrong\u003Esubstance-induced psychotic disorder\u003C/strong\u003E (alcoholic hallucinosis) include clear consciousness, preserved orientation, predominantly auditory hallucinations, and maintained insight into the relationship between symptoms and alcohol use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcohol withdrawal delirium\u003C/strong\u003E (delirium tremens) typically occurs 48-72 hours after cessation of alcohol and is characterised by confusion, disorientation, visual hallucinations, and autonomic instability. This patient has clear consciousness and predominantly auditory hallucinations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEarly-onset schizophrenia\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely for several reasons. First, the diagnosis of schizophrenia requires symptoms to be present for at least one month during the active phase and a total duration of illness of at least six months, including prodromal and residual phases. Second, the symptoms must not be directly attributable to substance use - in this case, the hallucinations are clearly temporally related to alcohol consumption. Third, patients with schizophrenia typically have poor insight into their illness, whereas this patient demonstrates good insight by recognising the connection between his symptoms and alcohol use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrug-induced delirium\u003C/strong\u003E would present with fluctuating consciousness, disorientation, and visual hallucinations. This patient\u0027s clear sensorium and preserved orientation make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute paranoid psychosis\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with prominent delusions and thought disorder in addition to hallucinations, with poor insight into the nature of symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESubstance-induced psychotic disorder typically resolves within days to weeks of alcohol cessation with supportive care and abstinence. Antipsychotic medications may be used temporarily for symptom control. The presence of clear consciousness, preserved insight, and predominantly auditory hallucinations helps distinguish it from other alcohol-related conditions and primary psychotic disorders.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Alcoholic hallucinosis typically presents with auditory hallucinations in a clear sensorium, unlike delirium tremens which involves clouded consciousness.","Insight is usually preserved in alcoholic hallucinosis, unlike in schizophrenia.","Alcoholic hallucinosis typically resolves within days to weeks of alcohol cessation, whereas primary psychotic disorders persist."],"references":["Saunders JB, Latt N. Alcohol misuse and dependence. Assessment and management. Australian Family Physician. 2002 Dec;31(12):1079-85."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94796"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14684"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94796","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94796"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-05T15:35:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-05T15:37:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7377"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112762"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1150","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1150"},"attributes":{"